07088nam a22009855i 9783110590364DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105903647 a10.1515/97831105903642doi  a(DE-B1597)492614  a(OCoLC)1089218814  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aWomen from the Parsonage :bPastors’ Daughters as Writers, Translators, Salonnières, and Educators /ced. by Cindy K. Renker, Susanne Bach. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VI, 220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tA Maiden’s Pastime: Susanna Elisabeth Zeidler (1657–1693) -- tElizabeth Singer Rowe (1674–1737): From Parsonage to Bestselling Author -- tPublic Ambition as Moral Obligation: The Intellectual Career of Elizabeth Carter (1717–1806) -- tMadame Necker (1737–1794): Educator, Salonnière, Mother, Writer, Charity Patron -- tDorothea Friderika Baldinger, née Gutbier (1743–1786): A “Woman Intellectual” in the Age of Enlightenment? -- tSophie Schwarz (1754–1789): “Wonderful Antagonism in My Own Soul” – Annotations to Sophie Schwarz’s Travel Journal -- tPoetics, Politics, Gender and Pedagogics in Friederike Brun’s (1765–1835) Autobiography Wahrheit aus Morgenträumen (1824) -- tJane Austen (1775–1817): A Novelist from the Parsonage -- tLouise Aston (1814–1871): A Liberal Author and Feminist -- t“I will never have another man in this house”. The Perpetual Curate Patrick Brontë and His Perpetual Daughter Charlotte (1816–1855) -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDer Band Women from the Parsonage hat eine klare Struktur, die mit vergleichbaren Parametern die Bildung untersucht, die es Pastorentöchtern im 19. Jahrhundert ermöglichte, sich über die Limitationen, wie Zugang zu Wissen, intellektueller Teilhabe und schriftstellerischer Taetigkeit, hinwegzusetzen.Vereint werden aktuelle Ansätze aus Geschichtswissenschaft, gender studies, Intersektionalitätsforschung und Psychobiografie.  aThis volume provides a new context for women’s writing from the seventeenth through the end of the nineteenth century, highlighting the significant role of the parsonage and the parson himself for women’s education in those centuries. Cindy K. Renker and Susanne Bach's collection of essays is the first of its kind on the education, lives, and works of highly accomplished daughters of Protestant clergymen. Since this volume only represents a limited number of women raised and educated in parsonages, it will surely encourage more investigation of other women writers, translators, educators, etc. with similar backgrounds. Moreover, since this book takes a comparative and transnational approach by focusing on different regions of Europe and different centuries. This collection of essays is thus aimed at scholars in multiple fields such as British literature, German studies, gender studies, the history of women’s education, and social and cultural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aChildren of clergyxEducation. 0aChildren of clergyxHistory. 0aChildren of clergyxIntellectual life. 0aFathers and daughtersxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aWomen.  abiography.  aeducation.  agender.1 aBach, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBach, Susanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCollins, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamrau, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Renata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/